<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-sensitivity">
	<title>Sensitivity to change</title>

	<objectives>
		<ol>
			<li>
				<p>
					Measure a function's responsiveness to small changes using differentials.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Interpret the derivative as a ratio of differentials to analyze behavior.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Use the sign of a derivative to identify increasing and decreasing intervals.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ol>
	</objectives>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			Calculus is often described as the mathematics of change. Many quantities in the world change in tandem with each other:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
					The pressure of a gas depends on its temperature and volume.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The demand for a product depends on its price.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The daily calories needed by an organism depends on its mass.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The speed of a car depends on the pressure applied to the gas pedal.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The growth of a bacterial population depends on the amount of nutrients available.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The amount of traffic congestion depends on the number of cars on the road.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The brightness of a lamp depends on the electrical power supplied to it.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The time for a computer to sort a list depends on the number of items in the list.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
			To understand these relationships, we need a way to quantify how <em>sensitive</em> one quantity is to changes in another: if we change one variable by a small amount, how much does another variable change in response?
		</p>
	</introduction>
	
	<subsection xml:id="subsec-sensitivity-between-two-points">
		<title>Sensitivity between two points</title>
		<aside>
			<p>
				Based on data from <url href="https://arachnoid.com/braking_physics/index.html">The Physics Behind Stopping a Car</url> by P. Lutus.
			</p>
		</aside>
		<p>
			When driving a car, the distance required to stop depends on the speed of the vehicle. A simple empirical model relates the stopping distance <m>L</m> (measured in car lengths, assuming an average car length of <m>14.7</m> feet) to the speed <m>v</m> (measured in miles per hour) by the formula
			<me>
				L = 0.0034v^2 + 0.15v
			</me>.
			To make it explicit that <m>L</m> depends on <m>v</m> (that is, <m>L</m> is a <term>function</term> of <m>v</m>), we can also write
			<me>
				L(v) = 0.0034v^2 + 0.15v
			</me>.
			We call <m>v</m> the <term>independent variable</term> and <m>L</m> or <m>L(v)</m> the <term>dependent variable</term>, since the value of <m>L</m> depends on the value of <m>v</m>.
		</p>
		<aside>
			<p>
				In general, when one quantity depends on another, there are two common ways to name this relationship. We can name the output directly, as in <m>y</m> depending on <m>x</m> and writing <m>y = y(x)</m>, or we can give the function a separate name and write <m>y = f(x)</m>.
			</p>
		</aside>
		<p>
			For example, if a car is traveling at <m>50</m> miles per hour, we have
			<md>
				<mrow>L(50) \amp = 0.0034\cdot 50^2 + 0.15\cdot 50</mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 16 \text{ car lengths}</mrow>
			</md>,
			so the model predicts a stopping distance of <m>16</m> car lengths (or approximately <m>235.2</m> feet).
		</p>
		<p>
			Now, we might wonder, if we were to change the speed, how much would the stopping distance change? For example, suppose the speed increases by five miles per hour, that is,
			<md>
				<mrow>\Delta v \amp = v\tsub{final} - v\tsub{init}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 55 - 50</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 5</mrow>
			</md>.
			
			Then the change in stopping distance would be
			<md>
				<mrow>\Delta L \amp = L\tsub{final} - L\tsub{init}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = L(55) - L(50)</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = (0.0034\cdot 55^2 + 0.15\cdot 55) - (0.0034\cdot 50^2 + 0.15\cdot 50)</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 2.535\text{ car lengths}</mrow>
			</md>.
			We can then find the <em>ratio</em> of the change in stopping distance to the change in speed:
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{\Delta L}{\Delta v} \amp = \frac{L(55) - L(50)}{55-50}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = \frac{2.535\text{ car lengths}}{5\text{ mph}}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 0.507\text{ car lengths per mph}</mrow>
			</md>.
			That is, each extra mile per hour of speed means it takes another half of a car length to stop. We can call this the <term>sensitivity</term> of the stopping distance to changes in speed.
		</p>
		<definition>
			<title>Sensitivity between two points</title>

			<statement>
				<p>
					If <m>y=f(x)</m>, then the <term>sensitivity</term> of <m>f</m> between the points <m>x=a</m> and <m>x=b</m> is defined as
					<me>
						\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x} = \frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b - a}
					</me>.
					
					That is, the sensitivity is the ratio of the change in the output to the change in the input over that interval. We often say this out loud as <sq>the sensitivity of <m>y</m> to changes in <m>x</m>.</sq>
				</p>
				<p>
					We will also use the notation <m>\dfrac{\Delta f}{\Delta x}</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<p>
			We can also visualize what we've just done by plotting the stopping distance function <m>L(v)</m>:
		</p>
		<aside>
			<p>
				Will figure out how to make this graph better.
			</p>
		</aside>
		<image width="75%">
			<prefigure label="stopping-distance" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
				<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
				<definition>f(x)=0.0034*x^2+0.15*x</definition>
				<definition>a = 50</definition>
				<definition>b = 55</definition>
				<coordinates bbox="(-10,-10,70,70)">
					<grid-axes xlabel="v" ylabel="L(v)"/>
					<graph at="graph" function="f" domain="(0,75)"/>
					<line p1="(a,f(a))" p2="(b,f(a))"/>
					<line p1="(b,f(a))" p2="(b,f(b))"/>
					<point p="(a,f(a))" alignment="ne"/>
					<point p="(b,f(b))" alignment="ne"/>
				</coordinates>
				</diagram>
			</prefigure>
		</image>
		<p>
			Notice that the sensitivity we've calculated is the <em>slope</em> of the line connecting the points <m>(v\tsub{init},L\tsub{init})</m> and <m>(v\tsub{final},L\tsub{final})</m>.
		</p>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="subsec-sensitivity-at-a-point">
		<title>Sensitivity at a point</title>
		<p>
			Our calculation of the sensitivity above was somewhat coarse. Over an increase of five miles per hour, the graph is not perfectly straight but gets gradually steeper as we go, so the sensitivity was gradually changing. In other words, our calculation mixes together several sensitivities rather than capturing the sensitivity <em>at</em> <m>50</m> miles per hour.
		</p>
		<p>
			If we want a more precise measurement, a natural idea is to look at smaller changes in speed. Over smaller and smaller changes, the graph looks more and more like a straight line, so the slope between the two points gives a better estimate of the sensitivity at that speed. Here's what happens if we use a change in speed of <m>\Delta v=0.1</m> mph:
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{\Delta L}{\Delta v} \amp = \frac{L(50.1) - L(50)}{50.1-50}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = \frac{0.049034\text{ car lengths}}{0.1\text{ mph}}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 0.49034\text{ car lengths per mph}</mrow>
			</md>.
		</p>
		<activity>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Estimate the sensitivity of the stopping distance using the following values of <m>\Delta v</m> (comparing with a speed of <m>v\tsub{init}=50</m> mph). What do you notice about the values you get?
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta v=0.01</m> mph
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta v=0.001</m> mph
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta v=-0.1</m> mph
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta v=-0.01</m> mph
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta v=-0.001</m> mph
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</activity>
		<p>
			You should have noticed in the previous activity that as the change in speed gets smaller, our estimated sensitivity approaches a particular value, which seems to be around <m>0.49</m> car lengths per mph. This is similar to what you saw in the previous section, when the circumference of the circle approached <m>2\pi</m> more and more closely as we made better and better approximations.
		</p>
		
		<p>
			Unfortunately, these are still approximations of the sensitivity. However, if we imagine zooming in <sq>infinitely close</sq> to the point <m>(50,16)</m>, we might imagine that the graph of <m>L(v)</m> would be perfectly straight at that point. So if we could somehow choose two points that are <sq>infinitely close</sq> to each other, then the slope of the line between these two points would be exact sensitivity.
		</p>
		<p>
			(Insert figure)
		</p>
		<p>
			We call these infinitely small changes <term>differentials</term>, and we represent them with a lowercase <m>\mathrm{d}</m>: in this case, we would write <m>\dd{v}</m> to denote an infinitesimal change in speed, and <m>\dd{L}</m> to denote the corresponding infinitesimal change in stopping distance. The ratio of these differentials would then be written <me>\dv{L}{v}</me>. We will call this the <term>sensitivity</term> at the single point where <m>v=50</m> miles per hour. We'll soon be able to show that when <m>v=50</m> mph, the actual sensitivity is exactly <m>0.49</m> car lengths per mph.
		</p>
		<definition xml:id="def-sensitivity-at-a-point">
			<title>Sensitivity at a point</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					If <m>y=f(x)</m>, the <term>sensitivity</term> of <m>f</m> at the point <m>x=a</m> is (for the time being) defined as
					<me>
						\dv{y}{x}\approx\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}
					</me>
					where <m>b</m> is <sq>infinitely close</sq> to <m>a</m>. This definition is currently somewhat vague, as we have not defined what it means to be <sq>infinitely close.</sq> We'll make this definition more precise later.
				</p>
				<p>
					We will also use the notation <m>\DS\dv{f}{x}</m> for this sensitivity.
				</p>
				<p>
					When we want to emphasize that the sensitivity is being evaluated at a particular point <m>x=a</m>, we will write <m>\eval{\DS\dv{y}{x}}_{x=a}</m> or <m>\eval{\DS\dv{f}{x}}_{x=a}</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>
		<p>
			Now, you might be a bit skeptical of this idea of using <sq>infinitely small</sq> changes. If so, you're in good company! This idea of using infinitesimal quantities has long been a controversial topic in mathematics. On one hand, infinity is notoriously difficult to get a handle on <mdash/> just how small is <sq>infinitely small</sq> anyway? On the other hand, allowing ourselves to work with these infinitesimal ideas has helped us solve a lot of tricky problems throughout history. By developing calculus, we'll be able to find a way to make these intuitive-but-somewhat-vague arguments more precise, which will allow us to use them with confidence to describe real-world phenomena in a variety of applied contexts.
		</p>
		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use this same process to estimate <m>\eval{\DS\dv{L}{v}}_{v=30}</m> and <m>\eval{\DS\dv{L}{v}}_{v=70}</m>. How does the sensitivity of stopping distance to changes in speed compare at these different speeds?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</activity>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="subsec-estimating-changes">
		<title>Estimating changes</title>
		<p>
			Once we have the sensitivity at a point, we can use it to estimate how much the output will change in response to a small change in the input. For example, let's assume we know that <m>\eval{\DS\dv{L}{v}}_{v=50}=0.49</m> car lengths per mph, and suppose we want to estimate how the stopping distance will respond to a change in speed of <m>\Delta v=0.5</m> mph. Since the sensitivity <m>\DS\dv{L}{v}</m> is supposed to be the ratio of <sq>infinitely small</sq> changes, we can write:
			<me>
				\dfrac{\Delta L}{\Delta v} \approx \DS\dv{L}{v}
			</me>
			Then we can rearrange the terms to get
			<me>
				\Delta L \approx \DS\dv{L}{v}\cdot \Delta v
			</me>.
			Substituting what we know, we have
			<md>
				<mrow>\Delta L \amp \approx 0.49\cdot 0.5</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 0.245\text{ car lengths}</mrow>.
			</md>
			Hence if we increase the speed from <m>50</m> mph to <m>50.5</m> mph, we can estimate that the stopping distance will increase by approximately <m>0.245</m> car lengths. We can of course check this by computing the actual change in stopping distance:
			<md>
				<mrow>\Delta L \amp=L(50.5) - L(50)</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 16.24585 - 16</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 0.24585\text{ car lengths}</mrow>.
			</md>
			Notice that our estimate of <m>0.245</m> car lengths is very close to the actual change of <m>0.24585</m> car lengths. It may seem redundant to estimate the change when we can compute the actual change, but in many cases, we don't have a formula for the function we're interested in, such as when we have only collected data. In those cases, understanding how sensitivity lets us estimate change is useful for making predictions in how the output will respond to a change in input.
		</p>
		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Suppose that our speed <em>decreases</em> from <m>50</m> mph to <m>49.2</m> mph. How much would we estimate the stopping distance to change? Would it increase or decrease? Use the sensitivity at <m>v=50</m>to make your estimate. Then check your estimate by computing the actual change in stopping distance.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</activity>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="subsec-the-sign-of-the-sensitivity">
		<title>The sign of the sensitivity</title>
		<p>
			We can gain important information by looking at the sign of the sensitivity. Suppose throughout that <m>y</m> is a function of <m>x</m>.
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
					If <m>\DS\dv{y}{x} \gt 0</m> throughout some interval <m>a\le x\le b</m>, then if we increase the value of <m>x</m>, the value of <m>y</m> will also increase. (Likewise, if we <em>decrease</em> the value of <m>x</m>, the value of <m>y</m> will also decrease.) Thus we say that <m>y</m> is an <term>increasing</term> function of <m>x</m> on that interval.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					If <m>\DS\dv{y}{x} \lt 0</m> throughout some interval <m>a\le x\le b</m>, then if we increase the value of <m>x</m>, the value of <m>y</m> will decrease, and vice versa. Thus we say that <m>y</m> is a <term>decreasing</term> function of <m>x</m> on that interval.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
			This interpretation is especially useful when the independent variable is time, since it allows us to determine whether a particular quantity is increasing or decreasing as time passes. For example, suppose the following graph shows <m>h</m>, the height (in feet) of a ball thrown into the air, as a function of <m>t</m>, the time elapsed in seconds:
		</p>
		<p>
			(Insert figure showing a quadratic position function)
		</p>
		<p>
			As we move from left to right on the graph, the slope <m>\DS\dv{h}{t}</m> of the graph changes:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
					At first, <m>\DS\dv{h}{t}</m> is positive, which means the ball is rising.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					At the top of the curve, <m>\DS\dv{h}{t}</m> is zero, which means the ball is momentarily stationary at the highest point of its arc.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					After that, <m>\DS\dv{h}{t}</m> is negative, which means the ball is falling.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
			Thus, when the independent variable is time, we can interpret the sensitivity as a <term>rate of change</term>; in this case, <m>\DS\dv{h}{t}</m> tells us the rate, in feet per second, at which the height of the ball is changing at any given moment.
		</p>
		<p>
			Notice that the terms <sq>increasing</sq> and <sq>decreasing</sq> describe a <em>relationship</em> between two variables. They do not mean that the output (the dependent variable) is literally <sq>going up</sq> or <sq>going down</sq> on its own. When the independent variable is time, this interpretation can feel natural, since time always moves forward and the dependent variable may change as time passes. But when the independent variable is something else, such as speed, neither variable may actually be changing at a given moment; rather, the output increases or decreases <em>in response</em> to a change in the input. You'll often hear the phrase <sq><m>y</m> is increasing</sq>, but it would be more careful to say <sq><m>y</m> is an increasing function of <m>x</m></sq>, since the increase in <m>y</m> is tied to an increase in <m>x</m>.
		</p>
	</subsection>

	<exercises>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Suppose <m>y=3x-2</m>, so <m>y</m> is a <term>linear function</term> of <m>x</m>.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the sensitivity of <m>y</m> to various changes in <m>x</m> by completing the following table.
					</p>
					<tabular halign="center">
					<row header="yes" bottom="minor">
						<cell><m>x=a</m></cell>
						<cell><m>x=b</m></cell>
						<cell><m>\Delta x</m></cell>
						<cell><m>\Delta y</m></cell>
						<cell><m>\dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</m></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>1</m></cell>
						<cell><m>2</m></cell>
						<cell></cell>
						<cell></cell>
						<cell></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>1</m></cell>
						<cell><m>1.1</m></cell>
						<cell></cell>
						<cell></cell>
						<cell></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>1</m></cell>
						<cell><m>1.01</m></cell>
						<cell></cell>
						<cell></cell>
						<cell></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><m>1</m></cell>
						<cell><m>0.99</m></cell>
						<cell></cell>
						<cell></cell>
						<cell></cell>
					</row>
					</tabular>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What do you notice about the values you get for the sensitivity in each case?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What does <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m>, the sensitivity of <m>y</m>, seem to be at the point <m>x=1</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What would be the sensitivity of <m>y</m> at the point <m>x=2</m>? Why? 
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What can you conclude about the sensitivity of <m>y=mx+b</m> at any point <m>x=a</m>? Why?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Suppose <m>y=5</m>, so <m>y</m> is a <term>constant function</term> of <m>x</m>. That is, no matter what the value of <m>x</m> is, the value of <m>y</m> is always <m>5</m>.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What will <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> be at any point <m>x=a</m>? Why?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What does the graph of <m>y=5</m> look like? How does this graph help you understand the sensitivity of <m>y</m> to changes in <m>x</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						If we rewrite <m>y</m> as <m>0x+5</m>, how does this help you understand the sensitivity of <m>y</m> to changes in <m>x</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						If <m>y=k</m> is a constant function of <m>x</m>, where <m>k</m> is any constant, what will the sensitivity of <m>y</m> be at any point <m>x=a</m>? Why?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Suppose <m>y=x^2</m>, so <m>y</m> is a <term>quadratic function</term> of <m>x</m>.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Estimate <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> at the point <m>x=1</m> by computing the ratios of small changes in the input and output. As the intervals get smaller and smaller, what number does the sensitivity seem to be approaching?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Repeat the above exercise to estimate <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> at the points <m>x=2</m> and <m>x=3</m>. What do you notice about the values you get for the sensitivity at these different points?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Without doing any calculations, what do you think the sensitivity of <m>y=x^2</m> will be at the point <m>x=0</m>? Why?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Conjecture a formula for <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> at any point <m>x=a</m>. Why do you think this formula is correct?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<title>Extra practice</title>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Estimate <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> for each of the following graphs at the given points by computing the ratios of small changes in the input and output. As the intervals get smaller and smaller, what number do the sensitivities seem to be approaching?
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>y=x^3</m>, at <m>x=-2</m> and <m>x=-1</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>y=\sqrt{x}</m>, at <m>x=9</m> and <m>x=12</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>y=\dfrac{1}{x}</m>, at <m>x=3</m> and <m>x=7</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>y=x^2-5x+4</m>, at <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=4</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					In this exercise, you'll interpret the sign of the sensitivity for various real-world contexts. For each one, determine whether the sensitivity should be positive, negative, or zero, and explain your answer. (Think: if you increase the independent variable, what would you expect to happen to the dependent variable?) Also give the units for the sensitivity.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{B}{P}</m>, where <m>B=</m> the brightness of a lamp (measured in lumens) and <m>P=</m> the electrical power supplied to the lamp (measured in watts)
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{q}{p}</m>, where <m>q=</m> the number of packages of gourmet coffee beans that are ordered by consumers and <m>p=</m> the price (in dollars per package) of the coffee beans
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{T}{t}</m>, where <m>T=</m> the temperature (in degrees Fahrenheit) of a baked potato and <m>t=</m> the number of minutes elapsed since the potato was placed in the oven
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{t}{T}</m>, where <m>t=</m> the number of minutes it takes to bake a potato and <m>T=</m> the temperature (in degrees Fahrenheit) of the oven
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{C}{h}</m>, where <m>C=</m> the number of calories in a candy bar and <m>h=</m> the elevation (in feet) of the candy bar above sea level
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Suppose the temperature in the Pacific Ocean can be described by the function <m>T(\ell)</m>, where <m>T</m> is the temperature in degrees Celsius and <m>\ell</m> is the latitude in degrees.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose that <m>T(60)=10</m>. Explain what this means in context, including correct units.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose that we also know that <m>\eval{\DS\dv{T}{\ell}}_{\ell=60}=-0.5</m>. Explain what this means in context, including correct units.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Estimate <m>T(62)</m> and <m>T(59)</m> using the sensitivity at <m>\ell=60</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
				The graph below shows <m>P(x)</m>, the profit (in thousands of dollars) earned by a company as a function of <m>x</m>, the number of units produced (in hundreds of units).
				</p>
				<p>
				(Insert graph: a curve that rises, flattens at a maximum, then decreases)
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What are the units of <m>\DS\dv{P}{x}</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>

			<task>
				<statement>
				<p>
					At which values of <m>x</m> does <m>\DS\dv{P}{x}</m> appear to be positive? Explain how you can tell from the graph. What does this mean practically for the company?
				</p>
				</statement>
			</task>

			<task>
				<statement>
				<p>
					At which values of <m>x</m> does <m>\DS\dv{P}{x}</m> appear to be negative? Explain how you can tell from the graph. What does this mean practically?
				</p>
				</statement>
			</task>

			<task>
				<statement>
				<p>
					Based on the graph, about how many units should the company produce in order to maximize profit, and what is that maximum profit? What is <m>\DS\dv{P}{x}</m> at that point?
				</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>

		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					The following table shows the concentration <m>C</m> of a certain drug in a patient's bloodstream as a function of time <m>t</m>. Here <m>t</m> is measured in hours and <m>C</m> is measured in milligrams per liter.
				</p>
				<p>
					(Insert table)
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Estimate <m>\eval{\DS\dv{C}{t}}_{t=3}</m> and explain its meaning in context, including correct units.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Estimate the concentration of the drug at <m>t=3.25</m> hours.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						At what time <m>t</m> do you expect <m>\DS\dv{C}{t}</m> to be zero? What is the real-world significance of this time?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					How does the sensitivity of <m>y=f(x)</m> from <m>x=a</m> to <m>x=b</m> compare to its sensitivity from <m>x=b</m> to <m>x=a</m>? Explain.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
	</exercises>
</section>

